:"28. januar 1289","1326":"1326","about 1305":"omkring 1305","1289":"1289","1267":"1267","1333":"1333","1298":"1298","1243":"1243","1342":"1342","Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Skotland","Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas, Lanarkshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1289–":"1289–Overleden","1289–Male":"1289–Overleden","1290–1342":"1290–1342","1297–1333":"1297–1333","1280–1393":"1280–1393","1305–1374":"1305–1374","1243–1298":"1243–1298","1267–1326":"1267–1326","1374":"1374","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","28 January 1289":"28 januari 1289","1326":"1326","about 1305":"circa 1305","1289":"1289","1267":"1267","1333":"1333","1298":"1298","1243":"1243","1342":"1342","Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas, Lanarkshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1289–":"1289–Deceased","1289–Male":"1289–Deceased","1290–1342":"1290–1342","1297–1333":"1297–1333","1280–1393":"1280–1393","1305–1374":"1305–1374","1243–1298":"1243–1298","1267–1326":"1267–1326","1374":"1374","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","28 January 1289":"28 January 1289","1326":"1326","about 1305":"about 1305","1289":"1289","1267":"1267","1333":"1333","1298":"1298","1243":"1243","1342":"1342","Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Douglas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called from their situation on a river named with Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black’ + <i>glas</i> ‘stream’ (a derivative of <i>glas</i> ‘blue’). There are several localities in Scotland and Ireland so named, but the one from which the surname is derived in most if not all cases is Douglas in Lanarkshire 20 miles south of Glasgow, the original stronghold of the influential Douglas family and their retainers.","History: The family taking their name from Douglas in Lanarkshire were of Flemish origin. They rose to great prominence in the 14th and 15th centuries, controlling the earldoms of Douglas, Morton, and Angus, and later, Queensberry."],"variants":[{"name":"Douglass","meanings":["Scottish and English (Durham and Northumbria): variant of   Douglas  .","History: William Douglass, a physician recognized for his identification and description of an epidemic of scarlet fever, was born <i>c.</i> 1691 in Gifford, Haddington County, Scotland, and settled in Boston in 1718. The abolitionist, orator, and journalist Frederick Douglass assumed the name after escaping from slavery in 1838 and traveling to Massachusetts. Son of a white father and a slave with some Indian blood, he was born Frederick Augustus Washington Bailey <i>c.</i> 1817 in Tuckahoe, MD."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Douglas Earl of Douglas was born in 1289, in Douglas Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland, his father, Lord William \"Le Hardi\" Douglas 5th Laird of Douglas, was 46 and his mother, Eleanor Lovaine, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Dunbar."},"e